The paper proposes a new algorithm for solving the nonconvex nonsmooth low-rank minimization problem, which is a common problem in machine learning and computer vision. The paper uses techniques from optimization and linear algebra to develop the algorithm, which makes it likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses concepts from information theory (such as the singular value thresholding problem) and numerical analysis (such as the use of a weight vector), which make it possible for the paper to belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents experimental results on both synthetic data and real images, which makes it possible for the paper to belong to the cs.SI (Signal Processing) sub-category.
